content: Great app - I'm much further along in my progress than I would ever have imagined. Actually beginning to toy with the idea of a job application .

This app updated with a penalty system - 'Hearts' (3 lives, and once you're out of hearts, there is an astonishingly punishing THREE HOURS refresh rate). I can't even practice on another module in the app because...I'm out of hearts for mistakes I made on another module. Other learning apps allow you to earn back lives - this one only offers you the opportunity to pay. I'm unwilling to wait three hours and then make one mistake so that I can wait another three hours. In a model like that, you're actually punishing learners who make a mistake by...taking away their learning. I never yet met a schoolteacher who punished their pupils by taking away their textbooks and expecting them to learn better. The app was clever, clear and responsive (you need to write code in order to learn coding well!). I liked the initial challenge and it was easy to dip in and out to learn new things. This change to a more punitive approach makes little sense, is clearly money-driven and doesn't encourage repeated use.

Update: the bugs are truly appalling and not close to being good enough for the price they charge. Whole sections won't accept the correct answer, or let you pass until you find out the bug. I can get through typing the f-bomb as long as I click "see solution" then progress. Correct solution will let you pass? Lol no. What kind of sucker expects correct syntax or their money's worth. For the money they're charging, having a javascript course devolve into uselessness, and not even working at all on Bluestacks, and working terribly on native android is disgraceful. Pros: attractive interface, enjoyable enough to use and probably good for total beginners who find programming daunting and are in a time crunch or hobbyists. If you learn well by rote this may help. Cons: That's all it is. Rote. You can parrot the answers because you answer the same question 50 times but do you really understand it on a deep level? Probably not. For the price I expect a full version in-browser or on Windows, especially now Bluestacks has failed me it is of no use to me on Android devices. The options to choose to answer with semicolon, comma etc are far too small and an accessibility nightmare. Buggy at times and rolls back on mini-lesson you just completed on a semi-regular basis (on both native Android device and Bluestacks) and update as I said the bugs are disgraceful. I'd hang my head releasing this for money As someone already proficient in HTML and CSS and some JS this is going to introduce you to basics and concepts. The jump from this to real world programming is going to be huge for a lot of people and I would say almost too steep - so just be aware of that and dont give up. You will need to move on the edx, Udemy or MS Learn to start more advanced problem solving and/or a lot of practice for real world application. You migh be able to read (some) code but writing your more advanced code is going to be beyond you without major further education imho. W3C schools is also your friend. The CSS section is far too basic and missing a lot of the better features of CSS3. HTML is also missing many elements and concepts - no site layout was properly covered. Judging by reviews, a lot of people are not even aware of this fact. You barely scratched the surface. Know this going in. It's a starting bite only. I want to love this. I like the concept, I like the design and I do enjoy it but I think for the price I expect better. I also echo the sentiment that review features are absolutely necessary to refresh and reinforce. I think my young nieces and nephews might enjoy this and could be a good introductory for younger school kids.

content: Hats off to the developer! Basic beginning with interesting challenges throughout and is thorough for beginners.

As a recently-fired Huffington Post journalist, this app has been a godsend.   My journalistic focus was intersectional dynamics (if you don't know what that is, you are part of the problem and you need to educate yourself ASAP). I was considered by many of my peers to be the most woke staff writer in our cubicle farm. I wish I could take the credit, but the true heroes were my social sciences profs at Berkeley (go bears!). They taught me that relentlessly pursuing and emphasizing anything that could even be perceived as problematic in some way--regardless of how trivial or vacuous it might seem--would allow me to play a crucial role in dismantling power structures through a lucrative career in social justice activism. And for a few years, it really worked!  In reality, it doesn't matter how good or bad this app is; the fact is, just installing it is easily the most progress I've made toward a real career since graduating high school. So thanks!

Originally, when prompted to, by the app, I gave a 5 star rating. However, 
upon returning to the app, I was told to continue, I now have to pay a 
monthly fee. I loved Mimo up until that point. If I had known this, i never 
would have downloaded it. There are far too many similar apps, for free, 
for me to justify paying for a subscription. Thank you for your response, 
however, you seem to have misunderstood what I was saying. What I had said, 
was although I enjoyed using your app, there is no way I would ever pay for 
it. Instead, I ended up finding another app, called solo learn. Just as 
many courses as you offer, if not more, yet it is 100% free. Their courses, 
also seem to be a lot more comprehensive, and a lot more clear, and easy to 
understand than the ones you offer. Realistically, in today's world of 
free, if you're going to make people pay for something that they can get 
for free, you better make sure that it is Leaps and Bounds above the 
competition, tragically, your app falls short. I must thank you though, had 
it not been for me downloading your app first I probably would not have 
found sololearn.

content:
Massively disappointed with the application here. As I'm somewhat familiar 
with C#, I felt it would be interesting to see how it was covered in the 
beginner/intermediate lessons here. Unfortunately, I barely got through the 
"you've literally just encountered your first computer" lessons before I 
was slapped with the paywall, as per most applications these days. I'd love 
to be able to cover whether it was useful or not, but it seems like this 
wasn't made for the purpose of spreading the knowledge of code, but to jump 
on the recent trend of coding lessons popping up everywhere, in the hopes 
of it paying off under a subscription fee on the same level as a triple-A 
MMO despite a great number of beginning programmers being poor, from 
impoverished regions, or children and adolescents, and thus unable to pay 
anyway. Maybe if there was a way to actually identify the educational value 
of the program beyond "this is a variable" basic computing knowledge, I 
could review it more favourably, but unfortunately, I couldn't even get 
past something I could have figured out through skimming Wikipedia before I 
was subjected to a shakedown for my lunch money if I actually wanted to 
learn anything at all. Glad there are free options online, because this 
isn't even worth the bandwidth I spent on the download when it's not even 
going to show off any actual educational content.

This app was great, untill the pay wall. Unable to progress unless you buy 
into their subscription process. Disappointing

This app is great for beginners (or perhaps people with a lot of 
programming knowledge, but I'm definitely not advanced). It breaks down the 
steps in learning how to build a website period every day I only spend 10 
to 15 minutes yet I feel like I'm learning a lot.
replyContent: Hi Emma! Many thanks for using Mimo and for submitting your review. Our team is glad to hear that you consider our app great for beginners. Have a wonderful day and keep on having fun while learning to code! Cheers! Your Mimo Team

bad and good content... I'm finding that I don't have much time as I used 
to so I would rather much enjoy something that's high quality and in one 
place. I hope the app won't let me down. We shall see. :) 7/15/18
